			<li class="last"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a></li>
		</ul>
	</div>
		</header>
	<div class="a-column " id="a-col">
	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-607445 post type-post status-publish hentry category-corporate-governance-other-topics category-cyclical-consumer-goods category-hedge-funds tag-art tag-artnews tag-bibliowicz-jessica-m tag-loeb-daniel-s tag-ruprecht-william-f tag-shareholder-rights-and-activism tag-sotheby tag-third-point-llc tag-weill-sanford-i per-bibliowicz-jessica-m per-loeb-daniel-s per-ruprecht-william-f per-weill-sanford-i des-art des-shareholder-rights-and-activism org-artnews org-sotheby org-third-point-llc" id="post-607445">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Bare Knuckles at Sotheby&#8217;s Auction House</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Alexandra Stevenson and Michael J. de la Merced			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-04-24T11:48:10+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 24, 2014 7:48 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 24, 2014 7:48 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sotheby/Sotheby-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sotheby/Sotheby-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sotheby/Sotheby-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002844658" width="592" height="392" alt="Andy Warholâs âLiz #1 (Early Colored Liz)â on the block at Sothebyâs, which faces a shareholder challenge on May 6."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="392"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Andy Warholâs âLiz #1 (Early Colored Liz)â on the block at Sothebyâs, which faces a shareholder challenge on May 6.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/04/24/i-s-s-backs-two-loeb-nominees-for-sothebys-board/" data-title="Bare Knuckles at Sotheby&#8217;s Auction House" data-description="Daniel S. Loeb, the biggest shareholder of Sothebyâs, has nominated himself and two others to the board of the auction house, which holds its annual meeting on May 6.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t21h24m" class="update">Updated, 9:24 p.m. | </span>Directors of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BID&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Sotheby's">Sothebyâs</a> gathered in their wood-paneled boardroom with an urgent goal: how to mollify Daniel S. Loeb, the outspoken hedge fund mogul who is the auction houseâs largest shareholder.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet on that day, in late February, even as the board was debating whether to give the investor the two board seats he had demanded, Mr. Loeb suddenly struck. He nominated three director candidates, officially declaring war against the art world stalwart.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That battle â being closely watched in Manhattan socialite and art circles as well as on Wall Street â is now heading to its final stages as both sides lobby other shareholders before the companyâs annual meeting on May 6.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday, Mr. Loeb gained a significant advantage as the influential proxy advisory firm Institutional Shareholder Services recommended that shareholders vote for two of the three board nominees he has proposed, including himself. (Glass-Lewis, I.S.S.âs rival, is, however, supporting the Sothebyâs slate.)</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sotheby2/Sotheby2-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sotheby2/Sotheby2-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sotheby2/Sotheby2-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002844662" width="190" height="281" alt="With a 9.6 percent stake, the mogul Daniel S. Loeb is Sothebyâs biggest shareholder."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="281"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">With a 9.6 percent stake, the mogul Daniel S. Loeb is Sothebyâs biggest shareholder.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Michael Nagle for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Loeb, 52, is no stranger to no-holds-barred corporate battles, but this one is different in several ways. For one, it is almost as much a test of his reputation as an art aficionado as it is of his skills as an investor.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Known for his focus on contemporary and feminist art, Mr. Loeb has regularly made ARTnewsâ list of the 200 biggest collectors. Works that have graced his Manhattan office or homes include a seven-foot-wide metallic pink-and-blue <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/k/jeff_koons/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Jeff Koons.">Jeff Koons</a> egg â which he reportedly sold for $5.5 million â and a Martin Kippenberger sculpture of a crucified frog.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As part of its defense, Sothebyâs has publicly questioned Mr. Loebâs art expertise, irking him in the process.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For Sothebyâs, the hedge fund challenge comes as the 270-year-old auction house is grappling with a seismic shift in the business of selling art. Fierce competition and the rapid sprouting of new millionaires and potential clients in emerging economies like China have forced auction houses to reconsider their traditional models.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSothebyâs is like an old master painting in desperate need of restoration,â Mr. Loeb has argued.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The battle is reverberating not just among investors but also within the exclusive and close-knit circles of the art world. Some have questioned whether Mr. Loeb, as an upstart, is doing whatâs best for the business of art.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI think what people may be concerned about is that although he is a significant collector, his primary focus is finance and he is not an art world insider,â said Jeff Rabin, a co-founder of the art consulting firm Artvest Partners.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Founded in London in 1744 to sell off several hundred rare books, Sothebyâs has been one of the most prestigious names in the art world. It is the oldest listed company on the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/n/new_york_stock_exchange/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the New York Stock Exchange.">New York Stock Exchange</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet it was hit hard during the financial crisis. For the last year, activist investors have circled the company, anticipating a broader shake-up of the art market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe big question for Sothebyâs is how to adapt to a changing market without losing what makes them special and different,â said John D. Shea, the chief executive of Proxy Mosaic, a firm that advises shareholders in activist situations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To Mr. Loeb, Sothebyâs has not adapted quickly enough, leaving it ripe for the sort of corporate agitation that has made billions for himself and investors in his firm, Third Point. His playbook: buying a large stake in a company, and using that position to call for shifts in strategy and, often, board seats.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">According to Mr. Loeb, Sothebyâs has fallen behind its chief rival, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/c/christies/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Christie's.">Christieâs</a>, in recent years, especially in the Impressionist and Modern art beloved by todayâs mega-collectors, like hedge fund moguls. For example, while Sothebyâs reported its biggest-ever night of contemporary <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/a/art_auctions/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about art auctions.">art auctions</a> in November, with $390 million in sales, Christieâs equivalent night fetched $691 million in sales. (Christieâs, however, is privately owned by the French businessman FranÃ§ois-Henri Pinault and does not report financial results.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Loeb has accused Sothebyâs of rebating the fees its takes for selling multimillion-dollar works, while also taking less of the buyerâs fees to attract more business. He has taken issue with the auction houseâs strategy of focusing on top clients and headline sales. He has even criticized board membersâ relatively low holdings of their own companyâs stock.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Sothebyâs view, Mr. Loeb has disrupted its business for months by contacting major employees and positioning himself as their new boss, while also suggesting that prominent art world figures consider becoming the auction houseâs chief executive.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the fall, he met with Jeff T. Blau, chief executive of the Related Companies, to discuss a possible move to Relatedâs Hudson Yards complex or the <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TWX&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Time Warner Inc">Time Warner</a> Center, according to people briefed on the matter.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Company officials have also complained that Mr. Loeb has sometimes misunderstood the business. Moving Sothebyâs out of its current headquarters, for example, would make life difficult, given how customized it already is for the auction house.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And they have alluded to accusations that Mr. Loeb has committed âgreenmail,â the frowned-upon practice of buying up big stakes in companies and then forcing them to buy the shares back. After winning an activist campaign at <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=YHOO&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Yahoo! Inc">Yahoo</a> â one of his biggest victories to date â the Internet company bought back the majority of Mr. Loebâs stake a year later for $1.2 billion, yielding a significant profit.</p>
<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sothebysjp/Sothebysjp-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sothebysjp/Sothebysjp-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/25/business/Sothebysjp/Sothebysjp-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002845000" width="592" height="395" alt="âBloodline: Big Family No. 3â by the Chinese artist Zhang Xiaogang, on preview at a Sothebyâs auction in Hong Kong this month."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">âBloodline: Big Family No. 3â by the Chinese artist Zhang Xiaogang, on preview at a Sothebyâs auction in Hong Kong this month.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Tyrone Siu/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Though the billionaire investor first met with Sothebyâs last August, he came out swinging in October, when, in a typically Loeb-like letter, he disclosed a 9.3 percent stake. He now has a 9.6 percent stake.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He accused the auction houseâs chairman and chief executive, William F. Ruprecht, of having outstayed his welcome while being paid a salary that âinvokes the long-gone era of imperial C.E.O.s.â Ultimately, he demanded Mr. Ruprechtâs resignation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sothebyâs responded by instituting a poison pill, a defense that would limit activist investors from owning more than 10 percent of a company, a move that Mr. Loeb sneered was a ârelic of the 1980s.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Unusually, Mr. Loeb then went quiet, even as another hedge fund manager, Mick McGuire of Marcato Capital Management, announced a multipronged plan for the company to generate $1.3 billion in cash for shareholders. Mr. McGuire, who has a 6.6 percent stake, said this week that he would vote with Mr. Loeb at the annual meeting.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By January, Sothebyâs announced its own initiative to return $450 million to shareholders through dividend payouts and stock buybacks, after concluding a financial review initiated by its new chief financial officer, Patrick S. McClymont.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe spoke with many of our shareholders, and we asked people for their thinking on these topics,â Mr. McClymont said at the time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Privately, Mr. Loeb was holding talks with Mr. McClymont and Domenico De Sole, the dapper co-founder of the luxury clothier <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/f/tom_ford/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Tom Ford.">Tom Ford</a> and Sothebyâs newly installed lead independent director. By winter, the hedge fund manager had dropped his demand that Mr. Ruprecht resign, a matter of some satisfaction for the company.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sothebyâs offered to make Mr. Loeb a director and to give him plum board committee assignments, including its nominating committee. But Mr. Loeb, irritated by what he perceived was a disinterest in listening to him, argued that a single directorship could not drive home real change, and repeatedly demanded two seats.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now the two sides are contesting three board seats.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Loeb has nominated himself and two associates, including Olivier Reza, a former investment banker whose jeweler family has done business with Sothebyâs. The auction houseâs slate includes Jessica Bibliowicz, a financier and daughter of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=C&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Citigroup Inc">Citigroup</a>âs former chief executive, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/w/sanford_i_weill/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Sanford I. Weill.">Sanford I. Weill</a>, and Robert S. Taubman, whose family rescued Sothebyâs from a hostile bid in the 1980s, but whose father was convicted in a big price-fixing scandal a decade ago.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Each side has fallen into the timeworn rhythms of a corporate proxy fight, flinging attacks at each other on an almost weekly basis. In its most recent counterpunch, Sothebyâs disclosed on Wednesday its preliminary first-quarter results, including a 34 percent jump in Impressionist and contemporary sales from the same time a year ago. Overall, net auction sales rose 40 percent, to $730 million, while the companyâs overall loss narrowed to about $6 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In its report on Thursday, I.S.S. wrote that while Mr. Loebâs plan lacked a solid vision, both his and Marcatoâs critiques still had merit. âIn the particulars of their criticisms of things like commission margin, there is credible reason to believe their larger criticism about strategic myopia has some credibility,â the advisory firm wrote.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To some outsiders, Sothebyâs seems to be receptive to some of its criticsâ recommendations. The question is whether its executives are making certain changes fast enough.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThere is a lot of minutiae with this proxy battle,â said Oliver Chen, a luxury goods analyst with Citigroup. âBut there are a lot of big-picture questions â for example, ensuring that the model has another 100 years ahead of it.â</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
